<br>
Is it a betrayal of one's god to stand against them and fight their other minions?  Perhaps, but I think it's a lot easier for an evil character to rationalize his fight against his own god and his own god's minions, based on just what those gods are the gods OF--Hate, Fear, War, Death.  By allowing themselves to be consumed (and consuming others with them) by these things in a raid on their deity's plane, are they not simultaneously honoring their god, even as they make an attempt to destroy that god and his local minions?<br>
<br>
I would agree that dark characters would make an obvious enemy of light characters and deities of Light (though right now the only &quot;Good&quot; deity you can kill is Tunare, and she's a toughy by all accounts).<br>
<br>
I think there enough ways to explain/rationalize raiding one's own deity's plane for evil guilds... and obviously, it was part of Verant's &quot;vision&quot; to have evil characters killing their own god (evident in the fact that shadow knights have to raid both the planes of Hate and Fear to get their weapon, and the fact that you don't get negative faction hits for Innoruuk/Cazic worshipping factions for doing so).<br>
<br>
Now, a supposed roleplay guild kicking out a character for not participating in a raid (for roleplay purposes) would just be stupid.  If the guild can't raid an area because a couple people don't want to fight their own god, then they probably shouldn't be trying to raid that area anyway... and if they can raid those areas with a couple people opting out for RP reasons, they ought to respect that decision and let them stay in the guild.<br>
